The paper deals with a Compressed Sensing (CS) problem known as Multiple Measurement Vectors (MMV) problem, which arises in joint estimation of multiple signal realizations when the signal samples have a common (joint) sparse support over a fixed known dictionary. This problem is related to several sub-fields of CS, such as Information Theory (cs.IT), Machine Learning (cs.LG), Signal Processing (cs.SP), Matrix Analysis (cs.MM), and Statistical Learning (cs.SI). Given that the paper focuses on the analysis of a specific MMV algorithm and its performance under different conditions, it is likely to be classified under cs.IT or cs.LG, which are the most general categories for theoretical CS papers. However, since the paper also provides numerical simulations to validate the theoretical results, it could also be classified under cs.SP or cs.MM, which are more focused on practical applications of CS. Finally, since the paper deals with statistical estimation and dictionary learning, it could also be classified under cs.SI, which is concerned with statistical inference and learning.
